[iron](/wiki/Iron \"Iron\")                               |\n\nA **falchion** is a type of two-handed [weapon](/wiki/Weapon \"Weapon\") that appears in *[SpliceHack](/wiki/SpliceHack \"SpliceHack\")* and *[Hack'EM](/wiki/Hack%27EM \"Hack'EM\")*.\n\nIn SpliceHack, the falchion uses the scimitar skill. In Hack'EM it uses the saber skill which was merged with the scimitar skill.\n\n[ ]\n\n## Contents\n\n- [1 Generation](#Generation)\n- [2 Strategy](#Strategy)\n- [3 History](#History)\n- [4 Origin](#Origin)\n\n## Generation\n\nFalchions are uncommon, appearing slightly less than scimitars.\n\nIn both variants, [Barbarians](/wiki/Barbarian \"Barbarian\") can start with falchion/scimitar combo as an alternative to the battle-axe/short sword weapon set.\n\n## Strategy\n\nIn Hack'EM it is possible to create one by #crafting two [scimitars](/wiki/Scimitar \"Scimitar\") together.\n\n## History\n\nThe falchion first appears in [SpliceHack](/wiki/SpliceHack \"SpliceHack\").\n\n## Origin\n\n[![Wikipedia](/images/thumb/f/f8/Fair-use-wikipedia-logo.png/50px-Fair-use-wikipedia-logo.png)](/wiki/File:Fair-use-wikipedia-logo.png \"Wikipedia\")\n\n[Wikipedia](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_Page \"wikipedia:Main Page\") has an article about:\n\n***[Falchion](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Falchion \"wikipedia:Falchion\")***\n\nThe term falchion refers to various designs of European swords, but generally describes single-edged one-handed blades, often with a slightly curved tip. In appearance, they could vary from a [scimitar](/wiki/Scimitar \"Scimitar\")-like weapon all the way to something resembling a meat cleaver. Curiously, while falchions are frequently depicted in medieval European artwork, only a few dozen survive to the current day, compared to thousands of double-edged blades (e.g. [long swords](/wiki/Long_sword \"Long sword\")).\n\n[![This article has been updated to reflect NetHack 3.6.6. Click here for more information.](/images/5/57/Nh366-icon.png)](/wiki/NetHackWiki:Next_version \"This article has been updated to reflect NetHack 3.6.6. Click here for more information.\")\n","html":"<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html class=\"client-nojs\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\">\n<head>\n<meta charset=\"UTF-8\"/>\n<title>Falchion - NetHack Wiki</title>\n<script>document.documentElement.className = document.documentElement.className.replace( /(^|\\s)client-nojs(\\s|$)/, \"$1client-js$2\" );</script>\n<script>(window.RLQ=window.RLQ||[]).push(function(){mw.config.set({\"wgCanonicalNamespace\":\"\",\"wgCanonicalSpecialPageName\":false,\"wgNamespaceNumber\":0,\"wgPageName\":\"Falchion\",\"wgTitle\":\"Falchion\",\"wgCurRevisionId\":159419,\"wgRevisionId\":159419,\"wgArticleId\":38404,\"wgIsArticle\":true,\"wgIsRedirect\":false,\"wgAction\":\"view\",\"wgUserName\":null,\"wgUserGroups\":[\"*\"],\"wgCategories\":[\"Pages with broken file links\",\"Nethack-366 articles\",\"SpliceHack\",\"Hack'EM\",\"Weapons\"],\"wgBreakFrames\":false,\"wgPageContentLanguage\":\"en\",\"wgPageContentModel\":\"wikitext\",\"wgSeparatorTransformTable\":[\"\",\"\"],\"wgDigitTransformTable\":[\"\",\"\"],\"wgDefaultDateFormat\":\"dmy\",\"wgMonthNames\":[\"\",\"January\",\"February\",\"March\",\"April\",\"May\",\"June\",\"July\",\"August\",\"September\",\"October\",\"November\",\"December\"],\"wgMonthNamesShort\":[\"\",\"Jan\",\"Feb\",\"Mar\",\"Apr\",\"May\",\"Jun\",\"Jul\",\"Aug\",\"Sep\",\"Oct\",\"Nov\",\"Dec\"],\"wgRelevantPageName\":\"Falchion\",\"wgRelevantArticleId\":38404,\"wgRequestId\":\"c7e2303803abb91bf0db1d4b\",\"wgCSPNonce\":false,\"wgIsProbablyEditable\":false,\"wgRelevantPageIsProbablyEditable\":false,\"wgRestrictionEdit\":[],\"wgRestrictionMove\":[],\"wgWikiEditorEnabledModules\":[],\"wgCategoryTreePageCategoryOptions\":\"{\\\"mode\\\":0,\\\"hideprefix\\\":20,\\\"showcount\\\":true,\\\"namespaces\\\":false}\"});mw.loader.state({\"site.styles\":\"ready\",\"noscript\":\"ready\",\"user.styles\":\"ready\",\"user\":\"ready\",\"user.options\":\"ready\",\"user.tokens\":\"loading\",\"medi